---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Framework" description="The AI Matrix framework: access, agency, and the four quadrants of global AI adoption.">
  <section class="container page-content">
    <div class="prose">
      <h1>The AI Matrix Framework</h1>

      <p class="lede">
        The AI Matrix positions countries on two independent dimensions — access
        and agency — revealing four distinct patterns of AI adoption. It was
        introduced in
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.5228571" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Simpson (2025)</a>
        and is updated here with each new Anthropic Economic Index release.
      </p>

      <h2>Two dimensions</h2>

      <h3>Access: how broadly AI reaches the population</h3>
      <p>
        Access measures the extent to which AI tools are available to a country's
        population, calculated as the log-transformed per-capita rate of
        conversations with Claude. Countries with high access have AI tools
        reaching a significant share of their population; countries with low
        access have AI usage concentrated among a small number of users.
      </p>

      <h3>Agency: how productively people engage</h3>
      <p>
        Agency measures the quality of engagement once access exists. It is a
        composite of four indicators: the proportion of conversations involving
        active co-creation (task iteration, learning, and validation combined),
        the proportion that are purely directive (inverted — lower is better),
        the task success rate, and the education level of prompts. Countries
        with high agency use AI as a collaborative tool; countries with low
        agency tend toward passive or directive interaction patterns.
      </p>

      <h2>Four quadrants</h2>

      <div class="quadrant-grid">
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--full-empowerment">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--full-empowerment">Full Empowerment</span></h3>
          <p>High access, high agency. AI tools are broadly available and people engage with them productively. The aspirational quadrant.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--passive-dependency">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--passive-dependency">Passive Dependency</span></h3>
          <p>High access, low agency. AI tools are widely available but usage patterns lean toward personal or directive interactions rather than productive co-creation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--elite-empowerment">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--elite-empowerment">Elite Empowerment</span></h3>
          <p>Low access, high agency. AI tools reach only a small share of the population, but those who use them engage productively — often for professional work.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="quadrant quadrant--full-dependency">
          <h3><span class="stage-badge stage-badge--full-dependency">Full Dependency</span></h3>
          <p>Low access, low agency. AI tools are neither broadly available nor productively used. Usage is often concentrated in coursework and education.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Why it matters</h2>
      <p>
        Most discussions of the "AI divide" focus only on access — who has AI and
        who doesn't. The AI Matrix shows this is half the picture. A country can
        have widespread access but low agency (passive dependency), or limited
        access but highly productive usage (elite empowerment). Effective AI
        policy requires understanding both dimensions.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the full methodology, including composite construction, threshold
        rules, and data sources, see the <a href="/methodology">methodology page</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .page-content {
    padding: var(--space-lg) 0;
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: var(--text-h3);
    color: var(--text-primary);
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .quadrant-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-md);
    margin: var(--space-md) 0 var(--space-lg);
  }

  .quadrant {
    padding: var(--space-md);
    background: var(--bg-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 8px;
  }

  .quadrant h3 {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xs);
  }

  .quadrant p {
    font-size: var(--text-small);
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .quadrant-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
